    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MACS empirically models the shift size of ChIP-Seq tags, and uses it to improve the spatial resolution of predicted binding sites... The distance between the modes of the Watson and Crick peaks in the alignment is defined as 'd', and MACS shifts all the tags by d/2 toward the 3' ends to the most likely protein-DNA interaction sites.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes MACS (2008), not MACS3. The paper does model fragment length 'd' empirically from tag distribution (cross-correlation of Watson/Crick strands), but the tool is 'MACS', not 'MACS3' with a 'predictd subcommand'. The functional concept (estimating d from strand-separated tag pileups) is correct, but the tool name and version are incorrect.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Estimate the DNA fragment length d in ChIP-Seq experiments by cross-correlation analysis of read pileups, a critical parameter that determines downstream peak calling accuracy and local background normalization. This skill uses MACS3's predictd subcommand to infer the typical dis",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:00:44.888273+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MACS takes advantage of this bimodal pattern to empirically model the shifting size to better locate the precise binding sites. Given a sonication size (bandwidth) and a high-confidence fold-enrichment (mfold), MACS slides 2bandwidth windows across the genome to find regions with tags more than mfold enriched relative to a random tag genome distribution. MACS randomly samples 1,000 of these high-quality peaks, separates their Watson and Crick tags, and aligns them by the midpoint between their Watson and Crick tag centers",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes MACS (2008), not MACS3. The paper does not mention a 'predictd' subcommand; instead, MACS performs fragment length estimation as part of its core algorithm. The functional role (cross-correlation-based fragment length inference) is present, but the tool name and subcommand structure differ from the paper's actual implementation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "macs3 predictd",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:00:44.888273+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Sometimes the same tag can be sequenced repeatedly, more times than expected from a random genome-wide tag distribution. Such tags might arise from biases during ChIP-DNA amplification and sequencing library preparation, and are likely to add noise to the final peak calls. Therefore, MACS removes duplicate tags in excess of what is warranted by the sequencing depth (binomial distribution p-value <10-5).",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes MACS (2008), not MACS3. MACS does remove duplicates as part of its peak detection workflow, but there is no separate 'filterdup' subcommand mentioned in the paper. The functional role (duplicate removal before peak calling) is correct, but the tool name and subcommand structure differ.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "macs3 filterdup",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:00:44.888273+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "Paper does not mention a 'pileup' subcommand or strand-extended coverage track generation as a separate MACS step. MACS performs tag shifting and peak calling but does not explicitly describe a pileup generation utility.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "macs3 pileup",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:00:44.888273+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "Paper does not mention 'bdgpeakcall' or bedgraph-based peak calling as a separate subcommand. MACS performs peak calling directly from tag distributions using Poisson statistics, not from pre-computed bedgraph files.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "macs3 bdgpeakcall",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:00:44.888273+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MACS empirically models the shift size of ChIP-Seq tags, and uses it to improve the spatial resolution of predicted binding sites. MACS also uses a dynamic Poisson distribution to effectively capture local biases in the genome, allowing for more robust predictions... MACS uses a dynamic parameter, \u03bb local, defined for each candidate peak",
      "asbval:note": "The paper confirms that fragment length estimation (d) is critical for spatial resolution and local bias modeling, consistent with the scope description.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When beginning ChIP-Seq analysis with single-end BED/SAM input and no prior knowledge of the library's fragment length. The fragment length is essential before generating coverage tracks and building local bias backgrounds, as it directly controls peak calling resolution (minimum",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:00:44.888273+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "Paper does not discuss paired-end sequencing or BEDPE format handling. The paper focuses on single-end short reads from Solexa/Illumina.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "fragment-length-estimation-cross-correlation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Input is paired-end BED (BEDPE format) \u2014 use fragment length from BEDPE read pairs directly instead.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:00:44.888273+00:00",
