      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/macs3-subcommand-chaining/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MACS is implemented in Python and freely available with an open source Artistic License at [16]. It runs from the command line and takes the following parameters: -t for treatment file (ChIP tags, this is the ONLY required parameter for MACS) and -c for control file containing mapped tags; --format for input file format in BED or ELAND (output) format (default BED); --name for name of the run (for example, FoxA1, default NA); --gsize for mappable genome size to calculate \u03bb BG from tag count (default 2.7G bp, approximately the mappable human genome size); --tsize for tag size (default 25); --bw for bandwidth, which is half of the estimated sonication size (default 300); --pvalue for p-value cutoff to call peaks (default 1e-5); --mfold for high-confidence fold-enrichment to find model peaks for MACS modelling (default 32); --diag for generating the table to evaluate sequence saturation (default off). In addition, the user has the option to shift tags by an arbitrary number (--shiftsize) without the MACS model (--nomodel), to use a global lambda (--nolambda) to call peaks",
      "asbval:note": "Original MACS (2008) offers parameter-level control (--bw, --pvalue, --mfold, --shiftsize, --nomodel, --nolambda) but does NOT expose subcommand-level modularity. The card claims MACS3 subcommand chaining, which is a different architecture than the monolithic MACS described in this paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "macs3-subcommand-chaining",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "fine-grained control over each step of duplicate filtering, fragment-length estimation, coverage pileup, local-background bias modeling, and statistical scoring",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:02:18.450799+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/narrow-peak-calling-score-threshold/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MACS uses a dynamic Poisson distribution to effectively capture local biases in the genome, allowing for more robust predictions... After MACS shifts every tag by d/2, it slides 2d windows across the genome to find candidate peaks with a significant tag enrichment (Poisson distribution p-value based on \u03bb BG, default 10-5). Overlapping enriched peaks are merged, and each tag position is extended d bases from its center.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes MACS peak calling using Poisson p-values and tag shifting/extension by d, but does not explicitly mention q-value bedgraph tracks, bdgpeakcall, or the specific workflow of converting bedgraph scores to narrowPeak format. The card describes a downstream MACS3 workflow (bdgpeakcall on bedgraph) that is not present in the original MACS paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "narrow-peak-calling-score-threshold",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Call narrow peaks from a q-value bedgraph track by applying a statistical significance cutoff and enforcing minimum peak length and gap constraints. This final step converts continuous score data into discrete peak regions for ChIP-Seq analysis.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:02:40.001208+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/narrow-peak-calling-score-threshold/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes MACS (2008), not MACS3. MACS3 is a later version with modular bedgraph-based tools (bdgpeakcall, bdgcmp, bdgbroadcall). These tools do not appear in the provided passages. The original MACS performs peak calling directly from tag files, not from bedgraph q-value tracks.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "narrow-peak-calling-score-threshold",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "macs3 bdgpeakcall",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:02:40.001208+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/narrow-peak-calling-score-threshold/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "bdgcmp is a MACS3 modular tool for comparing pileups and generating bedgraph tracks. The original MACS paper (2008) does not describe this tool or bedgraph output format. MACS outputs BED and XLS files, not bedgraph tracks.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "narrow-peak-calling-score-threshold",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "macs3 bdgcmp",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:02:40.001208+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/narrow-peak-calling-score-threshold/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "predictd is a MACS3 modular tool. The original MACS paper describes empirical modeling of shift size d as part of the main algorithm, not as a separate predictd command. The paper states 'MACS takes advantage of this bimodal pattern to empirically model the shifting size' but does not describe a standalone predictd tool.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "narrow-peak-calling-score-threshold",
