    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/narrow-peak-calling-score-threshold/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MACS uses a dynamic parameter, \u03bb local, defined for each candidate peak as: \u03bb local = max( \u03bb BG , [ \u03bb 1k ,] \u03bb 5k , \u03bb 10k )... MACS uses \u03bb local to calculate the p-value of each candidate peak and removes potential false positives due to local biases... Candidate peaks with p-values below a user-defined threshold p-value (default 10-5) are called, and the ratio between the ChIP-Seq tag count and \u03bb local is reported as the fold_enrichment.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes comparison of ChIP pileup against local lambda (\u03bb_local) using Poisson p-values, which is conceptually similar to the bedgraph workflow. However, the original MACS does not output bedgraph q-value tracks or use a separate bdgpeakcall step. The workflow described in the card is MACS3 modular architecture, not the original MACS algorithm.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "narrow-peak-calling-score-threshold",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "After generating a q-value bedgraph track from ChIP-Seq pileup versus local lambda comparison, and you need to identify statistically significant narrow peaks with defined boundaries.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:02:40.001208+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/narrow-peak-coordinate-validation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MACS is implemented in Python and freely available with an open source Artistic License at [16]. It runs from the command line and takes the following parameters: -t for treatment file (ChIP tags, this is the ONLY required parameter for MACS) and -c for control file containing mapped tags; --format for input file format in BED or ELAND (output) format (default BED)... The output includes one BED file containing the peak chromosome coordinates, and one xls file containing the genome coordinates, summit, p-value, fold_enrichment and FDR (if control is available) of each peak.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes MACS (not MACS3) generating peak output with coordinates and summit positions. The paper does not mention narrowPeak format, paired-end (BEDPE) input, or MACS3 specifically. The card claims MACS3 with narrowPeak and paired-end support; the paper describes MACS with BED/ELAND format and generic peak output (BED + xls files). MACS3 is a later version not discussed in this 2008 paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2008-9-9-r137",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "narrow-peak-coordinate-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Verify that MACS3 callpeak correctly generates narrowPeak output files with valid peak coordinates and summit positions after processing paired-end ChIP-Seq data.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:02:55.683338+00:00",
